Rotating $360^\circ$ is the same as doing nothing, so rotating $1050^\circ$ is the same as rotating $1050^\circ - 2\cdot 360^\circ = 330^\circ$.  Therefore, we have $\cos 1050^\circ = \cos (1050^\circ - 2\cdot 360^\circ) = \cos 330^\circ$.

Let $P$ be the point on the unit circle that is $330^\circ$ counterclockwise from $(1,0)$, and let $D$ be the foot of the altitude from $P$ to the $x$-axis, as shown below.

[asy]
pair A,C,P,O,D;
draw((0,-1.2)--(0,1.2),p=black+1.2bp,Arrows(0.15cm));
draw((-1.2,0)--(1.2,0),p=black+1.2bp,Arrows(0.15cm));
A = (1,0);
O= (0,0);
label("$x$",(1.2,0),SE);
label("$y$",(0,1.2),NE);

P = rotate(330)*A;
D = foot(P,A,-A);
draw(O--P--D);
draw(rightanglemark(O,D,P,2));
draw(Circle(O,1));
label("$O$",O,NW);
label("$P$",P,SE);
//label("$A$",A,SE);
label("$D$",D,N);
[/asy]

